# Web Design Rules

## ZERO DISCRETION POLICY

These rules have no exceptions. There is no scenario - not a "one-off"
component, not speed, not the style being "nearly the same" - that
permits duplicating CSS across components or inventing off-palette colors.

Prohibited judgement calls:
- "I'll define the style inline for now and move it later." - No. Shared styles go in `terminal.css` or a CSS module before the task is done.
- "I'll use a slightly different shade of amber here." - No. Use the exact palette value.
- "This element doesn't need a loading state." - No. Every async operation gets a loading indicator.
- "I'll use a UI component library for this one widget." - No. No Bootstrap, no Tailwind, no MUI. Custom CSS only to maintain the terminal aesthetic.
- "I'll add `color: red` inline on this element." - No. Use a CSS module class or a global terminal.css class.

---

## 1988 green phosphor terminal aesthetic

The visual language is a 1988 CRT terminal - not a dark mode web app, not
Bloomberg, not a modern "hacker" theme. Every design decision reinforces
the physical reality of a phosphor screen: green light, no decoration,
pure information density.

Colors - do not deviate from these values:
- Background: `#0a0f0a` (near-black with green tint)
- Primary text: `#33ff33` (bright phosphor green)
- Dim text: `#1a7a1a` (lower-brightness green for secondary info, labels)
- Orange accent: `#ff6600` (active states, selected rows, urgent priority, focused elements)
- Purple accent: `#cc44ff` (categories, tags, metadata)
- Border/divider: `#1a4a1a` (dark green lines)

CRT phosphor glow - applied to all visible text:
```css
text-shadow: 0 0 8px #33ff33, 0 0 2px #33ff33;
```
Orange and purple elements get their own matching glow:
```css
/* orange glow */
text-shadow: 0 0 8px #ff6600, 0 0 2px #ff6600;
/* purple glow */
text-shadow: 0 0 8px #cc44ff, 0 0 2px #cc44ff;
```

Font: `'VT323', 'Courier New', monospace` - everywhere, no exceptions.
Load VT323 from Google Fonts. It replicates the VT100 terminal character
appearance exactly.

Font size: 16px base (VT323 renders smaller than typical fonts at the same
size - 16px reads like 13px on a standard font).

No border-radius anywhere. Terminals are square.
No drop shadows beyond the phosphor text glow.
No gradients. No blur effects. No decorative icons or imagery.
No scanlines. No screen curvature.

Borders and dividers use plain CSS border with color `#1a4a1a`, or ASCII
box-drawing characters (`+`, `-`, `|`) in text where appropriate.

## CSS architecture

```
src/renderer/styles/
  terminal.css       <- Global variables, reset, base typography, shared utility classes
  components/        <- Per-component CSS modules (*.module.css)
```

**Global styles in `terminal.css`:**
CSS custom properties (variables) for the entire palette. Base reset.
Typography defaults. Shared utility classes used across 2+ components.

**Component styles in CSS modules (`*.module.css`):**
Styles that belong to exactly one component live in a `.module.css` file
next to the component file. Import via:
```typescript
import styles from './SubjectCard.module.css';
<div className={styles.card}>
```

Never duplicate a class between two `.module.css` files. If the same
visual pattern appears in two components, extract it to `terminal.css`.

Never use inline `style={{}}` props except for dynamically computed
values (e.g. a width percentage from a prop). Static styles always go
in CSS.

## Color usage

- Green (`#33ff33`): default text, normal status, active data, In Progress.
- Dim green (`#1a7a1a`): secondary labels, placeholder text, inactive rows.
- Orange (`#ff6600`): selected/focused elements, Urgent priority, Review
  status, warnings, the current page indicator in navigation.
- Purple (`#cc44ff`): category tags, metadata fields, Closed/Final status,
  archived items.
- Do not introduce a new color for any purpose. Map every new state to
  the closest existing palette entry: green for active/normal, orange for
  elevated/warning, purple for completed/categorized.

## Data tables

Every data table follows this structure:

```tsx
<div className={styles.tableContainer}>
  <table className={styles.table}>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th className={styles.sortableHeader} data-column="name">
          Name
        </th>
        <th>Status</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      {rows.map(row => (
        <tr
          key={row.id}
          className={styles.clickableRow}
          onClick={() => onRowClick(row.id)}
        >
          <td>{row.name}</td>
          <td><StatusBadge status={row.status} /></td>
        </tr>
      ))}
    </tbody>
  </table>
</div>
```

- `tableContainer`: `overflow-x: auto` so the table scrolls without
  breaking the page layout. Never apply `overflow-x` inline.
- `sortableHeader`: cursor pointer, sort indicator (small arrow glyph).
- `clickableRow`: cursor pointer, hover background change.
- Sticky header row: `position: sticky; top: 0; background: #141414; z-index: 10`.

## Status badges

Status and priority values are always rendered as a `<StatusBadge>`
component, never as raw text:

```tsx
<StatusBadge status="In Progress" />
<PriorityBadge priority="Urgent" />
```

Define these components in `src/renderer/components/StatusBadge.tsx` and
`src/renderer/components/PriorityBadge.tsx`. The color mapping lives in
the component, not scattered across templates.

## Empty states

When a list has no results, always render a structured empty state - never
just nothing or a hidden element:

```tsx
<div className={styles.emptyState}>
  <div className={styles.emptyStateLabel}>NO SUBJECTS FOUND</div>
  <div className={styles.emptyStateHint}>
    Create a subject to begin tracking research.
  </div>
</div>
```

## Loading states

While an async IPC call is in flight, show a loading indicator:

```tsx
{loading ? (
  <div className={styles.loadingState}>LOADING...</div>
) : (
  <SubjectTable subjects={subjects} />
)}
```

No spinners with gradients or animations beyond a simple blink/pulse.
Terminal aesthetic: text like `LOADING...` or a blinking cursor is preferred.

## UX principles applied

- **Density first**: default view shows as much data as possible without
  scrolling. No unnecessary whitespace.
- **Keyboard navigability**: all primary actions are reachable via keyboard.
  Tab order is logical.
- **No modal dialogs for destructive actions**: use an inline confirmation
  ("Press again to confirm") rather than a modal overlay.
- **No animations**: no transitions, no slide-ins, no fades. State changes
  are instant.

